In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = new Window(new AppShell());

        window.Created   += (s, e) => Log("Created");
        window.Activated  += (s, e) => Log("Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Log("Deactivated");
        window.Stopped    += (s, e) => Log("Stopped");
        window.Resumed    += (s, e) => Log("Resumed");
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => Log("Destroying");
        // Fires when the size or position changes
        window.SizeChanged += (s, e) => Log($"SizeChanged: {window.Width}x{window.Height}");

        return window;
    }

    static void Log(string transition)
        => System.Diagnostics.Debug.WriteLine($"[Window] {transition} at {DateTime.Now:T}");
}
```

**Typical event order:**

| Scenario | Events |
|---|---|
| App launch | `Created → Activated` |
| Backgrounded | `Deactivated → Stopped` |
| Foregrounded | `Resumed → Activated` |
| Closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |

**Tips:**
- Use `Debug.WriteLine` so output goes to the **Debug Output** window (VS) or `adb logcat` (Android) without shipping to production.
- If you need per-page granularity, the `Page` lifecycle (`OnAppearing` / `OnDisappearing`) complements these window-level events.
